# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: energy-management-software
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Benchmarking is used to measure performance using a specific indicator (cost per unit of measure, productivity per unit of measure, cycle time of x per unit of measure or defects per unit of measure) resulting in a metric of performance that is then compared to others.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Also referred to as "best practice benchmarking" or "process benchmarking," this process is used in management, in which organizations evaluate various aspects of their processes in relation to the processes of best-practice companies, usually within a peer group defined for comparison.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] This allows organizations to develop plans to make improvements or adopt specific best practices, usually with the aim of increasing some aspect of performance.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Benchmarking may be a one-off event, but it is often treated as a continuous process in which organizations continually seek to improve their practices.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] In project management benchmarking can also support the selection, planning and delivery of projects.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] In the process of best practice benchmarking, management identifies the best firms in their industry, or in another industry where similar processes exist, and compares the results and processes of those studied (the "targets") to one's own results and processes.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] In this way, they learn how well the targets perform and, more importantly, the business processes that explain why these firms are successful.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] According to National Council on Measurement in Education, benchmark assessments are short assessments used by teachers at various times throughout the school year to monitor student progress in some area of the school curriculum.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] These also are known as interim government.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] In 1994, one of the first technical journals named *Benchmarking* was published.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] An early example of benchmarking is the Auerbach Corporation's Standard EDP Reports, which were first developed in 1962.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] In 2008, a comprehensive survey on benchmarking was commissioned by The Global Benchmarking Network, a network of benchmarking centres representing 22 countries.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] The tools that are likely to increase in popularity the most over the next three years are Performance Benchmarking, Informal Benchmarking, SWOT, and Best Practice Benchmarking.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Over 60% of organizations that are not currently using these tools indicated they are likely to use them in the next three years.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Benchmarking mainly depends on SWOT analysis and will also be using in future for almost 4–5 years.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] There is no single benchmarking process that has been universally adopted.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] The wide appeal and acceptance of benchmarking has led to the emergence of benchmarking methodologies.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] One seminal book is Boxwell's *Benchmarking for Competitive Advantage* (1994).
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] The first book on benchmarking, written and published by Kaiser Associates, is a practical guide and offers a seven-step approach.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Robert Camp (who wrote one of the earliest books on benchmarking in 1989) developed a 12-stage approach to benchmarking.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] The cost of benchmarking can substantially be reduced through utilizing the many internet resources that have sprung up over the last few years.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] These aim to capture benchmarks and best practices from organizations, business sectors and countries to make the benchmarking process much quicker and cheaper.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] The technique initially used to compare existing corporate strategies with a view to achieving the best possible performance in new situations (see above), has recently been extended to the comparison of technical products.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] This process is usually referred to as "technical benchmarking" or "product benchmarking".
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Its use is well-developed within the automotive industry ("automotive benchmarking"), where it is vital to design products that match precise user expectations, at minimal cost, by applying the best technologies available worldwide.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Data is obtained by fully disassembling existing cars and their systems.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Such analyses were initially carried out in-house by car makers and their suppliers.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] However, as these analyses are expensive, they are increasingly being outsourced to companies who specialize in this area.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Outsourcing has enabled a drastic decrease in costs for each company (by cost sharing) and the development of efficient tools (standards, software).
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Benchmarking can be internal (comparing performance between different groups or teams within an organization) or external (comparing performance with companies in a specific industry or across industries).
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Benchmarking software can be used to organize large and complex amounts of information.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Software packages can extend the concept of benchmarking and competitive analysis by allowing individuals to handle such large and complex amounts or strategies.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Such tools support different types of benchmarking (see above) and can reduce the above costs significantly.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] The emerging technology of benchmarking engines automates the process of turning data into noteworthy comparative insights, sometimes even expressing those insights in English sentences.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Another approach to making comparisons involves using more aggregative cost or production information to identify strong and weak performing units.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] The two most common forms of quantitative analysis used in metric benchmarking are data envelopment analysis (DEA) and regression analysis.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] DEA estimates the cost level an efficient firm should be able to achieve in a particular market.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] In infrastructure regulation, DEA can be used to reward companies/operators whose costs are near the efficient frontier with additional profits.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Regression analysis estimates what the average firm should be able to achieve.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] With regression analysis, firms that performed better than average can be rewarded while firms that performed worse than average can be penalized.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Such benchmarking studies are used to create yardstick comparisons, allowing outsiders to evaluate the performance of operators in an industry.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Advanced statistical techniques, including stochastic frontier analysis, have been used to identify high and weak performers in industries, including applications to schools, hospitals, water utilities, and electric utilities.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] One of the biggest challenges in metric benchmarking is the variety of metric definitions used among companies or divisions.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] Definitions may change over time within the same organization due to changes in leadership and priorities.
[src:energy-management-software/benchmarking] The most useful comparisons can be made when metric definitions are consistent across the units being compared and remain unchanged over time, allowing improvements to be measured accurately.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] BAS functionality may keep a building's climate within a specified range, provide light to rooms based on occupancy, monitor performance and device failures, and provide malfunction alarms to building maintenance staff.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] A BAS works to reduce building energy and maintenance costs compared to a non-controlled building.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Most commercial, institutional, and industrial buildings built after 2000 include a BAS, whilst older buildings may be retrofitted with a new BAS.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] A building controlled by a BAS is often referred to as an "intelligent building", a "smart building", or (if a residence) a *smart home*.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Commercial and industrial buildings have historically relied on robust proven protocols (like BACnet) while proprietary protocols (like X-10) were used in homes.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] With the advent of wireless sensor networks and the Internet of Things, an increasing number of smart buildings are resorting to using low-power wireless communication technologies such as Zigbee, Bluetooth Low Energy and LoRa to interconnect the local sensors, actuators and processing devices.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Almost all multi-story green buildings are designed to accommodate a BAS for the energy, air and water conservation characteristics.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Electrical device demand response is a typical function of a BAS, as is the more sophisticated ventilation and humidity monitoring required of "tight" insulated buildings.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Most green buildings also use as many low-power DC devices as possible.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Even a passivhaus design intended to consume no net energy whatsoever will typically require a BAS to manage heat capture, shading and venting, and scheduling device use.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Building management systems are most commonly implemented in large projects with extensive mechanical, HVAC, and electrical systems.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Systems linked to a BMS typically represent 40% of a building's energy usage; if lighting is included, this number approaches to 70%.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] BMS systems are a critical component to managing energy demand.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Improperly configured BMS systems are believed to account for 20% of building energy usage, or approximately 8% of total energy usage in the United States.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] In addition to controlling the building's internal environment, BMS systems are sometimes linked to access control (turnstiles and access doors controlling who is allowed access and egress to the building) or other security systems such as closed-circuit television (CCTV) and motion detectors.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Fire alarm systems and elevators are also sometimes linked to a BMS for monitoring.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] In case a fire is detected then only the fire alarm panel could close dampers in the ventilation system to stop smoke spreading, shut down air handlers, start smoke evacuation fans, and send all the elevators to the ground floor and park them to prevent people from using them.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Building management systems have also included disaster-response mechanisms (such as base isolation) to save structures from earthquakes.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] In more recent times, companies and governments have been working to find similar solutions for flood zones and coastal areas at-risk to rising sea levels.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Self-adjusting floating environment draws from existing technologies used to float concrete bridges and runways such as Washington's SR 520 and Japan's Mega-Float.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Analog inputs are used to read a variable measurement.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Examples are temperature, humidity and pressure sensors which could be thermistor, 4–20 mA, 0–10 volt or platinum resistance thermometer (resistance temperature detector), or wireless sensors.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] A digital input indicates a device is on or off.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Some examples of digital inputs would be a door contact switch, a current switch, an air flow switch, or a voltage-free relay contact (dry contact).
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Digital inputs could also be pulse inputs counting the pulses over a period of time.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] An example is a turbine flow meter transmitting flow data as a frequency of pulses to an input.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Nonintrusive load monitoring is software relying on digital sensors and algorithms to discover appliance or other loads from electrical or magnetic characteristics of the circuit.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] It is however detecting the event by an analog means.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] These are extremely cost-effective in operation and useful not only for identification but to detect start-up transients, line or equipment faults, etc.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Occupancy sensors detect the presence, number, and sometimes location of people in a space to enable demand-controlled systems for lighting, HVAC, and energy management.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Traditional examples include passive infrared (PIR), ultrasonic, and CO2-based detectors, but advanced systems use low-resolution thermal imaging or area sensors to provide zone-level accuracy without capturing identifiable images, ensuring privacy compliance (e.g., GDPR).
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] These sensors output analog heat signatures or digital counts that integrate with building management systems via protocols like BACnet or wireless IoT networks, reducing energy use by up to 40% through precise ventilation and lighting control.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Analog outputs control the speed or position of a device, such as a variable frequency drive, an I-P (current to pneumatics) transducer, or a valve or damper actuator.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] An example is a hot water valve opening up 25% to maintain a setpoint.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Another example is a variable frequency drive ramping up a motor slowly to avoid a hard start.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Digital outputs are used to open and close relays and switches as well as drive a load upon command.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] An example would be to turn on the parking lot lights when a photocell indicates it is dark outside.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Another example would be to open a valve by allowing 24VDC/AC to pass through the output powering the valve.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Analog outputs could also be pulse type outputs emitting a frequency of pulses over a given period of time.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] An example is an energy meter calculating kWh and emitting a frequency of pulses accordingly.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Controllers are essentially small, purpose-built computers with input and output capabilities.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] These controllers come in a range of sizes and capabilities to control devices commonly found in buildings, and to control sub-networks of controllers.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Inputs allow a controller to read temperature, humidity, pressure, current flow, air flow, and other essential factors.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] The outputs allow the controller to send command and control signals to slave devices, and to other parts of the system.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Inputs and outputs can be either digital or analog.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Digital outputs are also sometimes called discrete depending on manufacturer.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Controllers used for building automation can be grouped in three categories: programmable logic controllers (PLCs), system/network controllers, and terminal unit controllers.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] However an additional device can also exist in order to integrate third-party systems (e.g. a stand-alone AC system) into a central building automation system.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Terminal unit controllers usually are suited for control of lighting and/or simpler devices such as a package rooftop unit, heat pump, VAV box, fan coil, etc.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] The installer typically selects one of the available pre-programmed personalities best suited to the device to be controlled, and does not have to create new control logic.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Occupancy is one of two or more operating modes for a building automation system; unoccupied, morning warmup, and night-time setback are other common modes.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Occupancy is usually based on time of day schedules.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] In occupancy mode, the BAS aims to provides a comfortable climate and adequate lighting, often with zone-based control so that users on one side of a building have a different thermostat (or a different system, or sub system) than users on the opposite side.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] A temperature sensor in the zone provides feedback to the controller, so it can deliver heating or cooling as needed.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] If enabled, morning warmup (MWU) mode occurs prior to occupancy.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] During morning warmup the BAS tries to bring the building to setpoint just in time for occupancy.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] The BAS often factors in outdoor conditions and historical experience to optimize MWU.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] This is also referred to as *optimized start*.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Some buildings rely on occupancy sensors to activate lighting or climate conditioning.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Given the potential for long lead times before a space becomes sufficiently cool or warm, climate conditioning is not often initiated directly by an occupancy sensor.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Lighting can be turned on, off, or dimmed with a building automation or lighting control system based on time of day, or on occupancy sensor, photosensors and timers.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] One typical example is to turn the lights in a space on for a half-hour since the last motion was sensed.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] A photocell placed outside a building can sense darkness, and the time of day, and modulate lights in outer offices and the parking lot.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Lighting is also a good candidate for demand response, with many control systems providing the ability to dim (or turn off) lights to take advantage of DR incentives and savings.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] In newer buildings, the lighting control can be based on the field bus Digital Addressable Lighting Interface (DALI).
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Lamps with DALI ballasts are fully dimmable.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] DALI can also detect lamp and ballast failures on DALI luminaires and signals failures.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Shading and glazing are essential components in the building system, they affect occupants' visual, acoustical, and thermal comfort and provide the occupant with a view outdoor.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Automated shading and glazing systems are solutions for controlling solar heat gains and glare.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] It refers to the use of technology to control external or internal shading devices (such as blinds, and shades) or glazing itself.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] The system has an active and rapid response to various changing outdoor data (such as solar, wind) and to changing interior environment (such as temperature, illuminance, and occupant demands).
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Building shading and glazing systems can contribute to thermal and lighting improvement from both energy conservation and comfort point of view.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Dynamic shading devices allow the control of daylight and solar energy to enter into built environment in relation to outdoor conditions, daylighting demands and solar positions.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] The common products include venetian blinds, roller shades, louvers, and shutters.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] They are mostly installed on the interior side of the glazing system because of the low maintenance cost, but also can be used on the exterior or a combination of both.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Most air handlers mix return and outside air so less temperature/humidity conditioning is needed.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] This can save money by using less chilled or heated water (not all AHUs use chilled or hot water circuits).
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Some external air is needed to keep the building's air healthy.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] To optimize energy efficiency while maintaining healthy indoor air quality (IAQ), demand control (or controlled) ventilation (DCV) adjusts the amount of outside air based on measured levels of occupancy.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Analog or digital temperature sensors may be placed in the space or room, the return and supply air ducts, and sometimes the external air.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Actuators are placed on the hot and chilled water valves, the outside air and return air dampers.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] The supply fan (and return if applicable) is started and stopped based on either time of day, temperatures, building pressures or a combination.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] All modern building automation systems have alarm capabilities.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] It does little good to detect a potentially hazardous or costly situation if no one who can solve the problem is notified.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Notification can be through a computer (email or text message), pager, cellular phone voice call, audible alarm, or all of these.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] For insurance and liability purposes all systems keep logs of who was notified, when and how.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Alarms may immediately notify someone or only notify when alarms build to some threshold of seriousness or urgency.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] At sites with several buildings, momentary power failures can cause hundreds or thousands of alarms from equipment that has shut down – these should be suppressed and recognized as symptoms of a larger failure.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Some sites are programmed so that critical alarms are automatically re-sent at varying intervals.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] For example, a repeating critical alarm (of an uninterruptible power supply in 'bypass') might resound at 10 minutes, 30 minutes, and every 2 to 4 hours thereafter until the alarms are resolved.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Security systems can be interlocked to a building automation system.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] If occupancy sensors are present, they can also be used as burglar alarms.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Because security systems are often deliberately sabotaged, at least some detectors or cameras should have battery backup and wireless connectivity and the ability to trigger alarms when disconnected.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Modern systems typically use power-over-Ethernet (which can operate a pan-tilt-zoom camera and other devices up to 30–90 watts) which is capable of charging such batteries and keeps wireless networks free for genuinely wireless applications, such as backup communication in outage.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Fire alarm panels and their related smoke alarm systems are usually hard-wired to override building automation.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] For example: if the smoke alarm is activated, all the outside air dampers close to prevent air coming into the building, and an exhaust system can isolate the blaze.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Similarly, electrical fault detection systems can turn entire circuits off, regardless of the number of alarms this triggers or persons this distresses.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Fossil fuel combustion devices also tend to have their own over-rides, such as natural gas feed lines that turn off when slow pressure drops are detected (indicating a leak), or when excess methane is detected in the building's air supply.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] ASHRAE's open protocol BACnet or the open protocol LonTalk specify how most such devices interoperate.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Modern systems use SNMP to track events, building on decades of history with SNMP-based protocols in the computer networking world.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Physical connectivity between devices was historically provided by dedicated optical fiber, ethernet, ARCNET, RS-232, RS-485 or a low-bandwidth special purpose wireless network.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Modern systems rely on standards-based multi-protocol heterogeneous networking such as that specified in the IEEE 1905.1 standard and verified by the nVoy auditing mark.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Proprietary hardware dominates the controller market.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Each company has controllers for specific applications.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Some are designed with limited controls and no interoperability, such as simple packaged roof top units for HVAC.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Software will typically not integrate well with packages from other vendors.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Cooperation is at the Zigbee/BACnet/LonTalk level only.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Current systems provide interoperability at the application level, allowing users to mix-and-match devices from different manufacturers, and to provide integration with other compatible building control systems.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] These typically rely on SNMP, long used for this same purpose to integrate diverse computer networking devices into one coherent network.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] With the growing spectrum of capabilities and connections to the Internet of Things, building automation systems were repeatedly reported to be vulnerable, allowing hackers and cybercriminals to attack their components.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Buildings can be exploited by hackers to measure or change their environment: sensors allow surveillance (e.g. monitoring movements of employees or habits of inhabitants) while actuators allow to perform actions in buildings (e.g. opening doors or windows for intruders).
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] Several vendors and committees started to improve the security features in their products and standards, including KNX, Zigbee and BACnet (see recent standards or standard drafts).
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] However, researchers report several open problems in building automation security.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] On November 11, 2019, a 132-page security research paper was released titled "I Own Your Building (Management System)" by Gjoko Krstic and Sipke Mellema that addressed more than 100 vulnerabilities affecting various BMS and access control solutions by various vendors.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] On November 24, 2025, a 161-page security research paper was released titled "Project Brainfog: Beyond the Facade - Exposing Smart Giants" by Gjoko Krstic that addressed more than 1000 vulnerabilities affecting two widely used BAS controllers by ABB Group.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] It is common for room automation systems to employ a touchscreen as the primary way of controlling each operation.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] On November 27, 2018, a 29-page research paper titled "A Scalable Room Occupancy Prediction with Transferable Time Series Decomposition of CO2 Sensor Data" was published by Irvan Bastian Arief, Margaret Hamilton, and Flora Salim.
[src:energy-management-software/building-automation] The paper introduced a novel approach to leveraging carbon dioxide (CO2) sensor data to predict room occupancy—enabling smarter building automation by estimating the number of occupants in a room at any given time.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] A **carbon footprint** (or **greenhouse gas footprint**) is a calculated value or index that makes it possible to compare the total amount of greenhouse gases that an activity, product, company or country adds to the atmosphere.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Carbon footprints are usually reported in tonnes of emissions (CO2-equivalent) per unit of comparison.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Such units can be, for example, *tonnes CO2-eq per year*, *per kilogram of protein for consumption*, *per kilometer travelled*, *per piece of clothing* and so forth.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] A product's carbon footprint includes the emissions for the entire life cycle.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] These run from the production along the supply chain to its final consumption and disposal.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Similarly, an organization's carbon footprint includes the direct as well as the indirect emissions that it causes.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The Greenhouse Gas Protocol (for carbon accounting of organizations) calls these *Scope 1, 2 and 3 emissions*.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] There are several methodologies and online tools to calculate the carbon footprint.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] They depend on whether the focus is on a country, organization, product or individual person.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] For example, the carbon footprint of a product could help consumers decide which product to buy if they want to be climate aware.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] For climate change mitigation activities, the carbon footprint can help distinguish those economic activities with a high footprint from those with a low footprint.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] So the carbon footprint concept allows everyone to make comparisons between the climate impacts of individuals, products, companies and countries.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It also helps people devise strategies and priorities for reducing the carbon footprint.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The carbon dioxide equivalent (CO2eq) emissions per unit of comparison is a suitable way to express a carbon footprint.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This sums up all the greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It includes all greenhouse gases, not just carbon dioxide.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] And it looks at emissions from economic activities, events, organizations and services.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] In some definitions, only the carbon dioxide emissions are taken into account.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] These do not include other greenhouse gases, such as methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Various methods to calculate the carbon footprint exist, and these may differ somewhat for different entities.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] For organizations it is common practice to use the Greenhouse Gas Protocol.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It includes three carbon emission scopes.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Scope 1 refers to *direct* carbon emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Scope 2 and 3 refer to *indirect* carbon emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Scope 3 emissions are those indirect emissions that result from the activities of an organization but come from sources which they do not own or control.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] For countries it is common to use consumption-based emissions accounting to calculate their carbon footprint for a given year.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based accounting using input-output analysis backed by super-computing makes it possible to analyse global supply chains.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Countries also prepare national GHG inventories for the UNFCCC.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The GHG emissions listed in those national inventories are only from activities in the country itself.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This approach is called *territorial-based accounting* or *production-based accounting.* It does not take into account production of goods and services imported on behalf of residents.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] *Consumption-based accounting* does reflect emissions from goods and services imported from other countries.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based accounting is therefore more comprehensive.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This comprehensive carbon footprint reporting including Scope 3 emissions deals with gaps in current systems.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Countries' GHG inventories for the UNFCCC do not include international transport.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Comprehensive carbon footprint reporting looks at the final demand for emissions, to where the consumption of the goods and services takes place.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Scientists report carbon footprints in terms of equivalents of tonnes of CO2 emissions (CO2-equivalent).
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] They may report them per year, per person, per kilogram of protein, per kilometer travelled, and so on.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] In the definition of carbon footprint, some scientists include only CO2.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] But more commonly they include several of the notable greenhouse gases.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] They can compare various greenhouse gases by using carbon dioxide equivalents over a relevant time scale, like 100 years.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Some organizations use the term *greenhouse gas footprint* or *climate footprint* to emphasize that all greenhouse gases are included, not just carbon dioxide.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The Greenhouse Gas Protocol includes all of the most important greenhouse gases.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] In comparison, the IPCC definition of *carbon footprint* in 2022 covers only carbon dioxide.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] That publication included only carbon dioxide in the definition of carbon footprint.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It justified this with the argument that other greenhouse gases were more difficult to quantify.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This is because of their differing global warming potentials.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] They also stated that an inclusion of all greenhouse gases would make the carbon footprint indicator less practical.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] But there are disadvantages to this approach.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] One disadvantage of not including methane is that some products or sectors that have a high methane footprint such as livestock appear less harmful for the climate than they actually are.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The greenhouse gas protocol is a set of standards for tracking greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The standards divide emissions into three *scopes (S*cope 1, 2 and 3) within the value chain.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Greenhouse gas emissions caused directly by the organization such as by burning fossil fuels are referred to as S*cope 1*.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Emissions caused indirectly by an organization, such as by purchasing secondary energy sources like electricity, heat, cooling or steam are called *Scope 2*.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Lastly, indirect emissions associated with upstream or downstream processes are called *Scope 3*.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Direct or *Scope 1* carbon emissions come from sources on the site that is producing a product or delivering a service.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] An example for industry would be the emissions from burning a fuel on site.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] On the individual level, emissions from personal vehicles or gas-burning stoves are Scope 1.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Indirect carbon emissions are emissions from sources upstream or downstream from the process being studied.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] They are also known as *Scope 2* or *Scope 3* emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Scope 2 emissions are the indirect emissions related to purchasing electricity, heat, or steam used on site.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Examples of upstream carbon emissions include transportation of materials and fuels, any energy used outside of the production facility, and waste produced outside the production facility.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Examples of downstream carbon emissions include any end-of-life process or treatments, product and waste transportation, and emissions associated with selling the product.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The GHG Protocol says it is important to calculate upstream and downstream emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Scope 3 emissions are all other indirect emissions derived from the activities of an organization.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] But they are from sources they do not own or control.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The GHG Protocol's *Corporate Value Chain (Scope 3) Accounting and Reporting Standard* allows companies to assess their entire value chain emissions impact and identify where to focus reduction activities.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Scope 3 emission sources include emissions from suppliers and product users.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] These are also known as the *value chain*.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Transportation of goods, and other indirect emissions are also part of this scope.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] In 2022 about 30% of US companies reported Scope 3 emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The International Sustainability Standards Board is developing a recommendation to include Scope 3 emissions in all GHG reporting.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The current rise in global average temperature is more rapid than previous changes.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It is primarily caused by humans burning fossil fuels.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The increase in greenhouse gases in the atmosphere is also due to deforestation and agricultural and industrial practices.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The two most notable greenhouse gases are carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Greenhouse gas emissions, and hence humanity's carbon footprint, have been increasing during the 21st century.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The Paris Agreement aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions enough to limit the rise in global temperature to no more than 1.5 °C above pre-industrial levels.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint concept makes comparisons between the climate impacts of individuals, products, companies and countries.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] A carbon footprint label on products could enable consumers to choose products with a lower carbon footprint if they want to help limit climate change.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] For meat products, as an example, such a label could make it clear that beef has a higher carbon footprint than chicken.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Understanding the size of an organization's carbon footprint makes it possible to devise a strategy to reduce it.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] For most businesses the vast majority of emissions do not come from activities on site, known as Scope 1, or from energy supplied to the organization, known as Scope 2, but from Scope 3 emissions, the extended upstream and downstream supply chain.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Therefore, ignoring Scope 3 emissions makes it impossible to detect all emissions of importance, which limits options for mitigation.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Large companies in sectors such as clothing or automobiles would need to examine more than 100,000 supply chain pathways to fully report their carbon footprints.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The importance of displacement of carbon emissions has been known for some years.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Scientists also call this carbon leakage.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The idea of a carbon footprint addresses concerns of carbon leakage which the Paris Agreement does not cover.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Carbon leakage occurs when importing countries outsource production to exporting countries.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The outsourcing countries are often rich countries while the exporters are often low-income countries.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Countries can make it appear that their GHG emissions are falling by moving "dirty" industries abroad, even if their emissions could be increasing when looked at from a consumption perspective.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Carbon leakage and related international trade have a range of environmental impacts.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] These include increased air pollution, water scarcity, biodiversity loss, raw material usage, and energy depletion.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Scholars have argued in favour of using both consumption-based and production-based accounting.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This helps establish shared producer and consumer responsibility.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Currently countries report on their annual GHG inventory to the UNFCCC based on their territorial emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This is known as the territorial-based or production-based approach.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Including consumption-based calculations in the UNFCCC reporting requirements would help close loopholes by addressing the challenge of carbon leakage.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The Paris Agreement currently does not require countries to include in their national totals GHG emissions associated with international transport.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] These emissions are reported separately.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] They are not subject to the limitation and reduction commitments of Annex 1 Parties under the Climate Convention and Kyoto Protocol.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint methodology includes GHG emissions associated with international transport, thereby assigning emissions caused by international trade to the importing country.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The calculation of the carbon footprint of a product, service or sector requires expert knowledge and careful examination of what is to be included.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Carbon footprints can be calculated at different scales.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] They can apply to whole countries, cities, neighborhoods and also sectors, companies and products.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Several free online carbon footprint calculators exist to calculate personal carbon footprints.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Software such as the "Scope 3 Evaluator" can help companies report emissions throughout their value chain.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The software tools can help consultants and researchers to model global sustainability footprints.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] In each situation there are a number of questions that need to be answered.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] These include which activities are linked to which emissions, and which proportion should be attributed to which company.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Software is essential for company management.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] But there is a need for new ways of enterprise resource planning to improve corporate sustainability performance.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] To achieve 95% carbon footprint coverage, it would be necessary to assess 12 million individual supply-chain contributions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This is based on analyzing 12 sectoral case studies.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The Scope 3 calculations can be made easier using input-output analysis.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This is a technique originally developed by Nobel Prize-winning economist Wassily Leontief.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based emission accounting traces the impacts of demand for goods and services along the global supply chain to the end-consumer.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It is also called consumption-based carbon accounting.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] In contrast, a *production-based approach* to calculating GHG emissions is not a carbon footprint analysis.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This approach is also called a *territorial-based approach.* The production-based approach includes only impacts physically produced in the country in question.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based accounting redistributes the emissions from production-based accounting.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It considers that emissions in another country are necessary for the home country's consumption bundle.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Consumer-based accounting is based on input-output analysis.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It is used at the highest levels for any economic research question related to environmental or social impacts.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Analysis of global supply chains is possible using consumption-based accounting with input-output analysis assisted by super-computing capacity.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Leontief created Input-output analysis (IO) to demonstrate the relationship between consumption and production in an economy.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It incorporates the entire supply chain.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It uses input-output tables from countries' national accounts.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It also uses international data such as UN Comtrade and Eurostat.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Input-output analysis has been extended globally to multi-regional input-output analysis (MRIO).
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Innovations and technology enabling the analysis of billions of supply chains made this possible.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Standards set by the United Nations underpin this analysis.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The analysis enables a *Structural Path Analysis.* This scans and ranks the top supply chain nodes and paths.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It conveniently lists hotspots for urgent action.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Input-output analysis has increased in popularity because of its ability to examine global value chains.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Life cycle assessment (LCA) is a methodology for assessing all environmental impacts associated with the life cycle of a commercial product, process, or service.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It is not limited to the greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It includes water pollution, air pollution, ecotoxicity and similar types of pollution.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Some widely recognized procedures for LCA are included in the ISO 14000 series of environmental management standards.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] A standard called ISO 14040:2006 provides the framework for conducting an LCA study.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] ISO 14060 family of standards provides further sophisticated tools.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Also the latest standard, ISO 14064:2018 has the right set of tools that will help reduce Carbon Emissions in Corporations.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] These are used to quantify, monitor, report and validate or verify GHG emissions and removals.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Greenhouse gas product life cycle assessments can also comply with specifications such as Publicly Available Specification (PAS) 2050 and the GHG Protocol Life Cycle Accounting and Reporting Standard.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] An advantage of LCA is the high level of detail that can be obtained on-site or by liaising with suppliers.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] However, LCA has been hampered by the artificial construction of a boundary after which no further impacts of upstream suppliers are considered.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This can introduce significant truncation errors.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] LCA has been combined with input-output analysis.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This enables on-site detailed knowledge to be incorporated.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] IO connects to global economic databases to incorporate the entire supply chain.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Critics argue that the original aim of promoting the personal carbon footprint concept was to shift responsibility away from corporations and institutions and on to personal lifestyle choices.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The fossil fuel company BP ran a large advertising campaign for the personal carbon footprint in 2004 which helped popularize this concept.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This strategy, employed by many major fossil fuel companies, has been criticized for trying to shift the blame for negative consequences of those industries on to individual choices.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Geoffrey Supran and Naomi Oreskes of Harvard University argue that concepts such as carbon footprints "hamstring us, and they put blinders on us, to the systemic nature of the climate crisis and the importance of taking collective action to address the problem".
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] While the focus on individual behaviour has shaped public discourse, scientific assessments emphasize that this approach alone is insufficient.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The IPCC notes that individual behavioural changes alone are insufficient to achieve deep emission reductions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Reducing emissions through behaviour is important, but eliminating combustion altogether through systemic change is critical to long-term climate goals.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] A focus on carbon footprints can lead people to ignore or even exacerbate other related environmental issues of concern.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] These include biodiversity loss, ecotoxicity, and habitat destruction.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It may not be easy to measure these other human impacts on the environment with a single indicator like the carbon footprint.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Consumers may think that the carbon footprint is a proxy for environmental impact.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] There can be trade-offs between reducing carbon footprint and environmental protection goals.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] One example is the use of biofuel, a renewable energy source that can reduce the carbon footprint of the energy supply but can also pose ecological challenges during its production.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This is because it is often produced in monocultures with ample use of fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Another example is offshore wind parks, which could have unintended impacts on marine ecosystems.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint analysis solely focuses on greenhouse gas emissions, unlike a life-cycle assessment which is much broader and looks at all environmental impacts.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Therefore, it is useful to stress in communication activities that the carbon footprint is just one in a family of indicators (e.g. ecological footprint, water footprint, land footprint, and material footprint), and should not be looked at in isolation.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] In fact, carbon footprint can be treated as one component of ecological footprint.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The "Sustainable Consumption and Production Hotspot Analysis Tool" (SCP-HAT) is a tool to place carbon footprint analysis into a wider perspective.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It includes a number of socio-economic and environmental indicators.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It offers calculations that are either consumption-based, following the carbon footprint approach, or production-based.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The database of the SCP-HAT tool is underpinned by input–output analysis.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This means it includes Scope 3 emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The IO methodology is also governed by UN standards.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It is based on input-output tables of countries' national accounts and international trade data such as UN Comtrade, and therefore it is comparable worldwide.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The term *carbon footprint* has been applied to limited calculations that do not include Scope 3 emissions or the entire supply chain.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This can lead to claims of misleading customers with regards to the real carbon footprints of companies or products.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Greenhouse gas emissions (GHG emissions) from human activities intensify the greenhouse effect which contributes to climate change.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Carbon dioxide (CO2) from burning fossil fuels (such as coal, oil, and natural gas) is the main cause of climate change.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The largest annual emissions are from China followed by the United States, which has higher emissions per capita.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The main producers fueling the emissions globally are large oil and gas companies.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Emissions from human activities have increased atmospheric carbon dioxide by about 50% over pre-industrial levels.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The growing levels of emissions have varied, but have been consistent among all greenhouse gases.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Over 60 billion tons were emitted in 2025, higher than any year before.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Total cumulative emissions from 1870 to 2022 were 703 GtC (2575 GtCO2), of which 484±20 GtC (1773±73 GtCO2) from fossil fuels and industry, and 219±60 GtC (802±220 GtCO2) from land use change.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Land-use change, such as deforestation, caused about 31% of cumulative emissions over 1870–2022, coal 32%, oil 24%, and gas 10%.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Carbon dioxide is the main greenhouse gas resulting from human activities.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It accounts for more than half of warming.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Methane (CH4) emissions have almost the same short-term impact.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Nitrous oxide (N2O) and fluorinated gases (F-gases) play a lesser role in comparison.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Emissions of carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide in 2023 were all higher than ever before.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The Carbon Trust has worked with UK manufacturers to produce "thousands of carbon footprint assessments".
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] As of 2014 the Carbon Trust state they have measured 28,000 certifiable product carbon footprints.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This NGO has also developed a labelling scheme which "supports informed consumer choices and business procurement decisions".
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Plant-based foods tend to have a lower carbon footprint than meat and dairy.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This holds true when comparing the footprint of foods in terms of their weight, protein content or calories.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The protein output of peas and beef provides an example.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Producing 100 grams of protein from peas emits just 0.4 kilograms of carbon dioxide equivalents (CO2eq).
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] To get the same amount of protein from beef, emissions would be nearly 90 times higher, at 35 kgCO2eq.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Only a small fraction of the carbon footprint of food comes from transport and packaging.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Most of it comes from processes on the farm, or from land use change.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This means the choice of what to eat has a larger potential to reduce carbon footprint than how far the food has traveled, or how much packaging it is wrapped in.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report found that global GHG emissions have continued to rise across all sectors.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The most rapid growth was in transport and industry.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] A key driver of global carbon emissions is affluence.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The IPCC noted that the wealthiest 10% in the world contribute between about one third to one half (36%–45%) of global GHG emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Researchers have previously found that affluence is the key driver of carbon emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It has a bigger impact than population growth.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] And it counters the effects of technological developments.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Continued economic growth mirrors the increasing trend in material extraction and GHG emissions**.** "Industrial emissions have been growing faster since 2000 than emissions in any other sector, driven by increased basic materials extraction and production," the IPCC said.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] There can be wide variations in emissions for transport of people.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] They include the length of the trip, the source of electricity in the local grid and the occupancy of public transport.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] In the case of driving the type of vehicle and number of passengers are factors.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Over short to medium distances, walking or cycling are nearly always the lowest carbon way to travel.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint of cycling one kilometer is usually in the range of 16 to 50 grams CO2eq per km.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] For moderate or long distances, trains nearly always have a lower carbon footprint than other options.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Carbon accounting, also called greenhouse gas accounting or GHG accounting, is a framework of methods to measure and track how much greenhouse gas (GHG) an organization emits.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It can also be used to track projects or actions to reduce emissions in sectors such as forestry or renewable energy.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Corporations, cities and other groups use these techniques to help limit climate change.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Organizations will often set an emissions baseline, create targets for reducing emissions, and track progress towards them.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The accounting methods enable them to do this in a more consistent and transparent manner.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The main reasons for GHG accounting are to address social responsibility concerns or meet legal requirements.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Public rankings of companies, financial due diligence and potential cost savings are other reasons.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] GHG accounting methods help investors better understand the climate risks of companies they invest in.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] They also help with net zero emission goals of corporations or communities.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Many governments around the world require various forms of reporting.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] There is some evidence that programs that require GHG accounting help to lower emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Markets for buying and selling carbon credits depend on accurate measurement of emissions and emission reductions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] These techniques can help to understand the impacts of specific products and services.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] They do this by quantifying their GHG emissions throughout their lifecycle (carbon footprint).
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] CO2 emissions of countries are typically measured on the basis of *production*.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This accounting method is sometimes referred to as *territorial emissions.* Countries use it when they report their emissions, and set domestic and international targets such as Nationally Determined Contributions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] *Consumption*-based emissions on the other hand are adjusted for trade.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] To calculate consumption-based emissions analysts have to track which goods are traded across the world.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Whenever a product is imported, all CO2 emissions that were emitted in the production of that product are included.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based emissions reflect the lifestyle choices of a country's citizens.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] According to the World Bank, the global average carbon footprint in 2014 was about 5 tonnes of CO2 per person, measured on a production basis.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The EU average for 2007 was about 13.8 tonnes CO2e per person.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] For the USA, Luxembourg and Australia it was over 25 tonnes CO2e per person.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] In 2017, the average for the USA was about 20 metric tonnes CO2e per person.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This is one of the highest per capita figures in the world.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The footprints per capita of countries in Africa and India were well below average.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Assuming a global population of around 9–10 billion by 2050, a carbon footprint of about 2–2.5 tonnes CO2e per capita is needed to stay within a 2 °C target.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] These carbon footprint calculations are based on a consumption-based approach using a Multi-Regional Input-Output (MRIO) database.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This database accounts for all greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions in the global supply chain and allocates them to the final consumer of the purchased commodities.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Efforts to reduce the carbon footprint of products, services, and organizations help limit climate change.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Such activities are called climate change mitigation.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Climate change mitigation, also called decarbonisation, is an action to limit the greenhouse gases in the atmosphere that cause climate change.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Climate change mitigation actions include conserving energy and replacing fossil fuels with clean energy sources.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Secondary mitigation strategies include changes to land use and removing carbon dioxide (CO2) from the atmosphere.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] 2022 assessments emphasize that global greenhouse gas emissions must peak before 2025 and decline by about 43% by 2030 to limit warming to 1.5 °C, requiring rapid transitions in energy, transport, and land-use systems.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Carbon offsetting can reduce a company's overall carbon footprint by providing it with a carbon credit.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] This compensates the company for carbon dioxide emissions by recognizing an equivalent reduction of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Reforestation, or restocking existing forests that have previously been depleted, is an example of carbon offsetting.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] A carbon footprint study can identify specific and critical areas for improvement.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It uses input-output analysis and scrutinizes the entire supply chain.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Such an analysis could be used to eliminate the supply chains with the highest greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The term *carbon footprint* was first used in a BBC vegetarian food magazine in 1999, though the broader concept of *ecological footprint*, which encompasses the carbon footprint, had been used since at least 1992, as also chronicled by journalist William Safire in the New York Times.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] In 2005, fossil fuel company BP hired the large advertising campaign Ogilvy to popularize the idea of a carbon footprint for individuals.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The campaign instructed people to calculate their personal footprints and provided ways for people to "go on a low-carbon diet".
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint is derived from the ecological footprint, which encompasses carbon emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint follows the logic of ecological footprint accounting, which tracks the resource use embodied in consumption, whether it is a product, an individual, a city, or a country.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] While in the ecological footprint, carbon emissions are translated into areas needed to absorb the carbon emissions, the carbon footprint on its own is expressed in the weight of carbon emissions per time unit.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] William Rees wrote the first academic publication about ecological footprints in 1992.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] Other related concepts from the 1990s are the "ecological backpack" and material input per unit of service (MIPS).
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The International Sustainability Standards Board (ISSB) aims to bring global, rigorous oversight to carbon footprint reporting.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It was formed out of the International Financial Reporting Standards.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It will require companies to report on their Scope 3 emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The ISSB has taken on board criticisms of other initiatives in its aims for universality.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It consolidates the Carbon Disclosure Standards Board, the Sustainability Accounting Standards Board and the Value Reporting Foundation.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It complements the Global Reporting Initiative.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] It is influenced by the Task Force on Climate-Related Financial Disclosures.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] As of early 2023, Great Britain and Nigeria were preparing to adopt these standards.
[src:energy-management-software/carbon-footprint] The *Expanded Total Equivalent Warming Impact* method has been used for an accurate evaluation of refrigerators emissions.
[src:energy-management-software/clearvue-zero] The platform combines energy monitoring with carbon accounting functions.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Utilities may signal demand requests to their customers in a variety of ways, including simple off-peak metering, in which power is cheaper at certain times of the day, and smart metering, in which explicit requests or changes in price can be communicated to customers.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The customer may adjust power demand by postponing some tasks that require large amounts of electric power, or may decide to pay a higher price for their electricity.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Some customers may switch part of their consumption to alternate sources, such as on-site solar panels and batteries.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In many respects, demand response can be put simply as a technology-enabled economic rationing system for electric power supply.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In demand response, voluntary rationing is accomplished by price incentives—offering lower net unit pricing in exchange for reduced power consumption in peak periods.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The direct implication is that users of electric power capacity not reducing usage (load) during peak periods will pay "surge" unit prices, whether directly, or factored into general rates.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Involuntary rationing, if employed, would be accomplished via rolling blackouts during peak load periods.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Practically speaking, summer heat waves and winter deep freezes might be characterized by planned power outages for consumers and businesses if voluntary rationing via incentives fails to reduce load adequately to match total power supply.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In 2013, it was expected that demand response programs will be designed to decrease electricity consumption or shift it from on-peak to off-peak periods depending on consumers' preferences and lifestyles.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In 2016 demand response was defined as "a wide range of actions which can be taken at the customer side of the electricity meter in response to particular conditions within the electricity system such as peak period network congestion or high prices".
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In 2010, demand response was defined as a reduction in demand designed to reduce peak demand or avoid system emergencies.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] It can be a more cost-effective alternative than adding generation capabilities to meet the peak and occasional demand spikes.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The underlying objective of DR is to actively engage customers in modifying their consumption in response to pricing signals.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The goal is to reflect supply expectations through consumer price signals or controls and enable dynamic changes in consumption relative to price.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In electricity grids, DR is similar to dynamic demand mechanisms to manage customer consumption of electricity in response to supply conditions, for example, having electricity customers reduce their consumption at critical times or in response to market prices.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The difference is that demand response mechanisms respond to explicit requests to shut off, whereas dynamic demand devices passively shut off when stress in the grid is sensed.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Demand response can involve actually curtailing power used or by starting on-site generation which may or may not be connected in parallel with the grid.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] This is a quite different concept from energy efficiency, which means using less power to perform the same tasks, on a continuous basis or whenever that task is performed.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] At the same time, demand response is a component of smart energy demand, which also includes energy efficiency, home and building energy management, distributed renewable resources, and electric vehicle charging.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Current demand response schemes are implemented with large and small commercial as well as residential customers, often through the use of dedicated control systems to shed loads in response to a request by a utility or market price conditions.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Services (lights, machines, air conditioning) are reduced according to a preplanned load prioritization scheme during the critical time frames.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] An alternative to load shedding is on-site generation of electricity to supplement the power grid.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Under conditions of tight electricity supply, demand response can significantly decrease the peak price and, in general, electricity price volatility.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Demand response is generally used to refer to mechanisms used to encourage consumers to reduce demand, thereby reducing the peak demand for electricity.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Since electrical generation and transmission systems are generally sized to correspond to peak demand (plus margin for forecasting error and unforeseen events), lowering peak demand reduces overall plant and capital cost requirements.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Depending on the configuration of generation capacity, however, demand response may also be used to increase demand (load) at times of high production and low demand.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Some systems may thereby encourage energy storage to arbitrage between periods of low and high demand (or low and high prices).
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Bitcoin mining is an electricity intensive process to convert computer hardware infrastructure, software skills and electricity into electronic currency.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Bitcoin mining is used to increase the demand during surplus hours by consuming cheaper power.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] There are three types of demand response - emergency demand response, economic demand response and ancillary services demand response.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Emergency demand response is employed to avoid involuntary service interruptions during times of supply scarcity.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Economic demand response is employed to allow electricity customers to curtail their consumption when the productivity or convenience of consuming that electricity is worth less to them than paying for the electricity.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Ancillary services demand response consists of a number of specialty services that are needed to ensure the secure operation of the transmission grid and which have traditionally been provided by generators.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In most electric power systems, some or all consumers pay a fixed price per unit of electricity independent of the cost of production at the time of consumption.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The consumer price may be established by the government or a regulator, and typically represents an average cost per unit of production over a given timeframe (for example, a year).
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Consumption therefore is not sensitive to the cost of production in the short term (e.g. on an hourly basis).
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] A pure economist might extrapolate the concept to hypothesize that consumers served under these fixed-rate tariffs are endowed with theoretical "call options" on electricity, though in reality, like any other business, the customer is simply buying what is on offer at the agreed price.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] A customer in a department store buying a $10 item at 9.00 am might notice 10 sales staff on the floor but only one occupied serving him or her, while at 3.00 pm the customer could buy the same $10 article and notice all 10 sales staff occupied.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In virtually all power systems electricity is produced by generators that are dispatched in merit order, i.e., generators with the lowest marginal cost (lowest variable cost of production) are used first, followed by the next cheapest, etc., until the instantaneous electricity demand is satisfied.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In most power systems the wholesale price of electricity will be equal to the marginal cost of the highest cost generator that is injecting energy, which will vary with the level of demand.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Thus the variation in pricing can be significant: for example, in Ontario between August and September 2006, wholesale prices (in Canadian Dollars) paid to producers ranged from a peak of $318 per MW·h to a minimum of - (negative) $3.10 per MW·h.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] It is not unusual for the price to vary by a factor of two to five due to the daily demand cycle.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] A negative price indicates that producers were being charged to provide electricity to the grid (and consumers paying real-time pricing may have actually received a rebate for consuming electricity during this period).
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] This generally occurs at night when demand falls to a level where all generators are operating at their minimum output levels and some of them must be shut down.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The negative price is the inducement to bring about these shutdowns in a least-cost manner.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The latter study found that even small shifts in peak demand would have a large effect on savings to consumers and avoided costs for additional peak capacity: a 1% shift in peak demand would result in savings of 3.9%, billions of dollars at the system level.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] An approximately 10% reduction in peak demand (achievable depending on the elasticity of demand) would result in systems savings of between $8 and $28 billion.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] While the net benefits would be significantly less than the claimed $35 billion, they would still be quite substantial.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In Ontario, Canada, the Independent Electricity System Operator has noted that in 2006, peak demand exceeded 25,000 megawatts during only 32 system hours (less than 0.4% of the time), while maximum demand during the year was just over 27,000 megawatts.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The ability to "shave" peak demand based on reliable commitments would therefore allow the province to reduce built capacity by approximately 2,000 megawatts.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In an electricity grid, electricity consumption and production must balance at all times; any significant imbalance could cause grid instability or severe voltage fluctuations, and cause failures within the grid.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Total generation capacity is therefore sized to correspond to total peak demand with some margin of error and allowance for contingencies (such as plants being off-line during peak demand periods).
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Operators will generally plan to use the least expensive generating capacity (in terms of marginal cost) at any given period, and use additional capacity from more expensive plants as demand increases.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Demand response in most cases is targeted at reducing peak demand to reduce the risk of potential disturbances, avoid additional capital cost requirements for additional plants, and avoid use of more expensive or less efficient operating plants.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Consumers of electricity will also pay higher prices if generation capacity is used from a higher-cost source of power generation.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Demand response may also be used to increase demand during periods of high supply and low demand.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Some types of generating plant must be run at close to full capacity (such as nuclear), while other types may produce at negligible marginal cost (such as wind and solar).
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Since there is usually limited capacity to store energy, demand response may attempt to increase load during these periods to maintain grid stability.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] For example, in the province of Ontario in September 2006, there was a short period of time when electricity prices were negative for certain users.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Energy storage such as pumped-storage hydroelectricity is a way to increase load during periods of low demand for use during later periods.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Use of demand response to increase load is less common, but may be necessary or efficient in systems where there are large amounts of generating capacity that cannot be easily cycled down.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Some grids may use pricing mechanisms that are not real-time, but easier to implement (users pay higher prices during the day and lower prices at night, for example) to provide some of the benefits of the demand response mechanism with less demanding technological requirements.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In the UK, Economy 7 and similar schemes that attempt to shift demand associated with electric heating to overnight off-peak periods have been in operation since the 1970s.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] More recently, in 2006 Ontario began implementing a "smart meter" program that implements "time-of-use" (TOU) pricing, which tiers pricing according to on-peak, mid-peak and off-peak schedules.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] During the winter, on-peak is defined as morning and early evening, mid-peak as midday to late afternoon, and off-peak as nighttime; during the summer, the on-peak and mid-peak periods are reversed, reflecting air conditioning as the driver of summer demand.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] As of May 1, 2015, most Ontario electrical utilities have completed converting all customers to "smart meter" time-of-use billing with on-peak rates about 200% and mid-peak rates about 150% of the off-peak rate per kWh.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Australia has national standards for Demand Response (AS/NZS 4755 series), which has been implemented nationwide by electricity distributors for several decades, e.g. controlling storage water heaters, air conditioners and pool pumps.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In 2016, how to manage electrical energy storage (e.g., batteries) has been added into the series of standards.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Energy consumers need some incentive to respond to such a request from a demand response provider.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Demand response incentives can be formal or informal.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The utility might create a tariff-based incentive by passing along short-term increases in the price of electricity, or they might impose mandatory cutbacks during a heat wave for selected high-volume users, who are compensated for their participation.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Other users may receive a rebate or other incentive based on firm commitments to reduce power during periods of high demand, sometimes referred to as *negawatts* (the term was coined by Amory Lovins in 1985).
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] For example, California introduced its own ELRP, where upon an emergency declaration enrolled customers get a credit for lowering their electricity use ($1 per kWh in 2021, $2 in 2022).
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Commercial and industrial power users might impose load shedding on themselves, without a request from the utility.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Some businesses generate their own power and wish to stay within their energy production capacity to avoid buying power from the grid.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Some utilities have commercial tariff structures that set a customer's power costs for the month based on the customer's moment of highest use, or peak demand.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] This encourages users to flatten their demand for energy, known as energy demand management, which sometimes requires cutting back services temporarily.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Smart metering has been implemented in some jurisdictions to provide real-time pricing for all types of users, as opposed to fixed-rate pricing throughout the demand period.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In this application, users have a direct incentive to reduce their use at high-demand, high-price periods.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Many users may not be able to effectively reduce their demand at various times, or the peak prices may be lower than the level required to induce a change in demand during short time periods (users have low price sensitivity, or elasticity of demand is low).
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Automated control systems exist, which, although effective, may be too expensive to be feasible for some applications.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Smart grid applications improve the ability of electricity producers and consumers to communicate with one another and make decisions about how and when to produce and consume electrical power.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] This emerging technology will allow customers to shift from an event-based demand response where the utility requests the shedding of load, towards a more 24/7-based demand response where the customer sees incentives for controlling load all the time.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Although this back-and-forth dialogue increases the opportunities for demand response, customers are still largely influenced by economic incentives and are reluctant to relinquish total control of their assets to utility companies.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] One advantage of a smart grid application is time-based pricing.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Customers who traditionally pay a fixed rate for consumed energy (kWh) and requested peak load can set their threshold and adjust their usage to take advantage of fluctuating prices.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] This may require the use of an energy management system to control appliances and equipment and can involve economies of scale.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Another advantage, mainly for large customers with generation, is being able to closely monitor, shift, and balance load in a way that allows the customer to save peak load and not only save on kWh and kW/month but be able to trade what they have saved in an energy market.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Again, this involves sophisticated energy management systems, incentives, and a viable trading market.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Smart grid applications increase the opportunities for demand response by providing real time data to producers and consumers, but the economic and environmental incentives remain the driving force behind the practice.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] One of the most important means of demand response in the future smart grids is electric vehicles.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Aggregation of this new source of energy, which is also a new source of uncertainty in the electrical systems, is critical to preserving the stability and quality of smart grids, consequently, the electric vehicle parking lots can be considered a demand response aggregation entity.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The modern power grid is making a transition from the traditional vertically integrated utility structures to distributed systems as it begins to integrate higher penetrations of renewable energy generation.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] These sources of energy are often diffusely distributed and intermittent by nature.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] These features introduce problems in grid stability and efficiency which lead to limitations on the amount of these resources which can be effectively added to the grid.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In a traditional vertically integrated grid, energy is provided by utility generators which are able to respond to changes in demand.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Generation output by renewable resources is governed by environmental conditions and is generally not able to respond to changes in demand.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Responsive control over noncritical loads that are connected to the grid has been shown to be an effective strategy able to mitigate undesirable fluctuations introduced by these renewable resources.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In this way instead of the generation responding to changes in demand, the demand responds to changes in generation.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In order to implement demand response systems, coordination of large numbers of distributed resources through sensors, actuators, and communications protocols becomes necessary.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] To be effective, the devices need to be economical, robust, and yet still effective at managing their tasks of control.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In addition, effective control requires a strong capability to coordinate large networks of devices, managing and optimizing these distributed systems from both an economic and a security standpoint.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In addition, the increased presence of variable renewable generation drives a greater need for authorities to procure more ancillary services for grid balance.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] One of these services is contingency reserve, which is used to regulate the grid frequency in contingencies.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] As the ratio of inverter-based generation compared to conventional generation increases, the mechanical inertia used to stabilize frequency decreases.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] When coupled with the sensitivity of inverter-based generation to transient frequencies, the provision of ancillary services from other sources than generators becomes increasingly important.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Technologies are available, and more are under development, to automate the process of demand response.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Such technologies detect the need for load shedding, communicate the demand to participating users, automate load shedding, and verify compliance with demand-response programs.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] GridWise and EnergyWeb are two major federal initiatives in the United States to develop these technologies.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Universities and private industry are also doing research and development in this arena.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Scalable and comprehensive software solutions for DR enable business and industry growth.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Some utilities are considering and testing automated systems connected to industrial, commercial and residential users that can reduce consumption at times of peak demand, essentially delaying draw marginally.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Although the amount of demand delayed may be small, the implications for the grid (including financial) may be substantial, since system stability planning often involves building capacity for extreme peak demand events, plus a margin of safety in reserve.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Such events may only occur a few times per year.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The process may involve turning down or off certain appliances or sinks (and, when demand is unexpectedly low, potentially increasing usage).
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] For example, heating may be turned down or air conditioning or refrigeration may be turned up (turning up to a higher temperature uses less electricity), delaying slightly the draw until a peak in usage has passed.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Although this is an experimental program, at scale these solutions have the potential to reduce peak demand considerably.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The success of such programs depends on the development of appropriate technology, a suitable pricing system for electricity, and the cost of the underlying technology.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Bonneville Power experimented with direct-control technologies in Washington and Oregon residences, and found that the avoided transmission investment would justify the cost of the technology.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Other methods to implementing demand response approach the issue of subtly reducing duty cycles rather than implementing thermostat setbacks.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] These can be implemented using customized building automation systems programming, or through swarm-logic methods coordinating multiple loads in a facility (e.g.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Similar approach can be implemented for managing air conditioning peak demand in summer peak regions.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Pre-cooling or maintaining slightly higher thermostat setting can help with the peak demand reduction.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In 2008 it was announced that electric refrigerators will be sold in the UK sensing dynamic demand which will delay or advance the cooling cycle based on monitoring grid frequency but they are not readily available as of 2018.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Industrial customers are also providing demand response.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] For example, Alcoa's Warrick Operation is participating in MISO as a qualified demand response resource, and the Trimet Aluminium uses its smelter as a short-term nega-battery.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The selection of suitable industries for demand response provision is typically based on an assessment of the so-called value of lost load.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Some data centers are located far apart for redundancy and can migrate loads between them, while also performing demand response.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Shedding loads during peak demand is important because it reduces the need for new power plants.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] To respond to high peak demand, utilities build very capital-intensive power plants and lines.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Peak demand happens just a few times a year, so those assets run at a mere fraction of their capacity.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Electric users pay for this idle capacity through the prices they pay for electricity.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] According to the Demand Response Smart Grid Coalition, 10%–20% of electricity costs in the United States are due to peak demand during only 100 hours of the year.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] DR is a way for utilities to reduce the need for large capital expenditures, and thus keep rates lower overall; however, there is an economic limit to such reductions because consumers lose the productive or convenience value of the electricity not consumed.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Thus, it is misleading to only look at the cost savings that demand response can produce without also considering what the consumer gives up in the process.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] It is estimated that a 5% lowering of demand would have resulted in a 50% price reduction during the peak hours of the California electricity crisis in 2000–2001.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] With consumers facing peak pricing and reducing their demand, the market should become more resilient to intentional withdrawal of offers from the supply side.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Residential and commercial electricity use often vary drastically during the day, and demand response attempts to reduce the variability based on pricing signals.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Electric systems and grids typically scale total potential production to meet projected peak demand (with sufficient spare capacity to deal with unanticipated events).
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] By "smoothing" demand to reduce peaks, less investment in operational reserve will be required, and existing facilities will operate more frequently.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] In addition, significant peaks may only occur rarely, such as two or three times per year, requiring significant capital investments to meet infrequent events.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The report estimates that in 2004 potential demand response capability equaled about 20,500 megawatts (MW), 3% of total U.S. peak demand, while actual delivered peak demand reduction was about 9,000 MW (1.3% of peak), leaving ample margin for improvement.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] It is further estimated that load management capability has fallen by 32% since 1996.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Factors affecting this trend include fewer utilities offering load management services, declining enrollment in existing programs, the changing role and responsibility of utilities, and changing supply/demand balance.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] To encourage the use and implementation of demand response in the United States, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) issued Order No.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] 745 in March 2011, which requires a certain level of compensation for providers of economic demand response that participate in wholesale power markets.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] The order is highly controversial and has been opposed by a number of energy economists, including Professor William W.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Hogan at Harvard University's Kennedy School.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Professor Hogan asserts that the order overcompensates providers of demand response, thereby encouraging the curtailment of electricity whose economic value exceeds the cost of producing it.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Professor Hogan further asserts that Order No.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] 745 is anticompetitive and amounts to "...an application of regulatory authority to enforce a buyer's cartel." Several affected parties, including the State of California, have filed suit in federal court challenging the legality of Order 745.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] A debate regarding the economic efficiency and fairness of Order 745 appeared in a series of articles published in The Electricity Journal.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Circuit Court of Appeals vacated Order 745 in its entirety.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Whether the Court of Appeals erred in holding that the rule issued by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission is arbitrary and capricious.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] On January 25, 2016, the United States Supreme Court in a 6-2 decision in *FERC v.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Electric Power Supply Ass'n* concluded that the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission acted within its authority to ensure "just and reasonable" rates in the wholesale energy market.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] 2222 on September 17, 2020, enabling distributed energy resources to participate in regional wholesale electricity markets.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Market operators submitted initial compliance plans by early 2022.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] As of December 2009 National Grid had 2369 MW contracted to provide demand response, known as STOR, the demand side provides 839 MW (35%) from 89 sites.
[src:energy-management-software/demand-response] Of this 839 MW approximately 750 MW is back-up generation with the remaining being load reduction.
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] Cyril Colin and Karim El Alami founded Elum Energy in Paris in 2016.
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] Both had studied at École Polytechnique before going on to the University of California, Berkeley, where they worked on energy systems and watched California's grid shift toward intermittent renewables.
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] Their first installation went in at a factory in Tangier, Morocco.
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] In 2017 the company took seed money from Kima Ventures and Colin won the *Jeune Ingénieur Créateur* prize from the Fondation Norbert Ségard, a French engineering foundation.
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] Over the following years the company moved into Sub-Saharan Africa, Latin America and Asia-Pacific, reaching 1,000 commissioned projects by 2023.
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] In September 2024, Elum Energy raised $13 million in a Series B round led by Energize Capital, a Chicago-based climate-tech fund, with follow-on from Alter Equity and Cota Capital.
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] The following July, the Île-de-France region invested a further €3.5 million through its Fonds Décarbonation, a €150 million vehicle co-financed by Bpifrance, EDF and Crédit Agricole.
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] The company's hardware line, ePowerControl, is a family of embedded controllers that regulate power flows between the components of a hybrid solar site in real time.
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] Different versions cover grid-tied storage (ES), off-grid microgrids (MC), zero-export installations (ZE) and utility-scale power plant control (PPC).
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] The controllers work with inverters and batteries from most major manufacturers, which PV Magazine described as a competitive advantage over proprietary systems.
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] ePowerMonitor is a cloud SCADA for remote portfolio management.
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] The technology was tested by laboratories at École Polytechnique and UC Berkeley and was the subject of a patent application.
[src:energy-management-software/elum-energy] PitchBook put total cumulative funding at $23.2 million across 12 investors.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Energy management software often provides tools for reducing energy costs and consumption for buildings, communities or industries.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] By analyzing data from solar monitoring systems, companies gain a precise picture of both energy production and system performance.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] This makes it possible to measure savings potential and offers a clear snapshot of the installation's financial health.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] EMS collects energy data and uses it for three main purposes: Reporting, Monitoring and Engagement.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Reporting may include verification of energy data, benchmarking, and setting high-level energy use reduction targets.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Monitoring may include trend analysis and tracking energy consumption to identify cost-saving opportunities.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Engagement can mean real-time responses (automated or manual), or the initiation of a dialogue between occupants and building managers to promote energy conservation.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] One engagement method that has recently gained popularity is the real-time energy consumption display available in web applications or an onsite energy dashboard/display.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Energy Management Software collects historic and/or real-time interval data, with intervals varying from quarterly billing statements to minute-by-minute smart meter readings.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] In addition to energy consumption, an EMS collects data related to variables that impact energy consumption such as number of people in the building, outside temperature, number of produced units, and more.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] The data are collected from interval meters, a building automation system, directly from utilities, directly from sensors on electrical circuits, or other sources.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Past bills can be used to provide a comparison between pre- and post-EMS energy consumption.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Through Energy Data Analytics, EMS assists the users in the composition of mathematical formulas for analyzing, forecasting and tracking energy conservation measures to quantify the success of the measure, once implemented.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Reporting tools are targeted at owners and executives who want to automate energy and emissions auditing.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Cost and consumption data from a number of buildings can be aggregated or compared with the software, saving time relative to manual reporting.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] EMS offers more detailed energy information than utility billing can provide; another advantage is that outside factors affecting energy use, such as weather condition or building occupancy, can be accounted for as part of the reporting process.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] This information can be used to prioritize energy savings initiatives and balance energy savings against energy-related capital expenditures.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Bill verification can be used to compare metered consumption against billed consumption.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Bill analysis can also demonstrate the impact of different energy costs, for example by comparing electrical demand charges to consumption costs.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Greenhouse gas (GHG) accounting can calculate direct or indirect GHG emissions, which may be used for internal reporting or enterprise carbon accounting.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Monitoring tools track and display real-time and historical data.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Often, EMS includes various benchmarking tools, such as energy consumption per square foot, weather normalization or more advanced analysis using energy modelling algorithms to identify anomalous consumption.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Seeing exactly when energy is used, combined with anomaly recognition, can allow Facility or Energy Managers to identify savings opportunities.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Initiatives such as demand shaving, replacement of malfunctioning equipment, retrofits of inefficient equipment, and removal of unnecessary loads can be discovered and coordinated using the EMS.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] For example, an unexpected energy spike at a specific time each day may indicate an improperly set or malfunctioning timer.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] These tools can also be used for Energy Monitoring and Targeting.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] EMS uses models to correct for variable factors such as weather when performing historical comparisons to verify the effect of conservation and efficiency initiatives.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] EMS may offer alerts, via text or email messages, when consumption values exceed pre-defined thresholds based on consumption or cost.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] These thresholds may be set at absolute levels, or use an energy model to determine when consumption is abnormally high or low.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] More recently, smartphones and tablets are becoming mainstream platforms for EMS.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Engagement can refer to automated or manual responses to collected and analyzed energy data.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Building control systems can respond as readily to energy fluctuation as a heating system can respond to temperature variation.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Demand spikes can trigger equipment power-down processes, with or without human intervention..
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Furthermore, modern energy management platforms are evolving to include integrated action management systems that bridge the gap between identifying a data anomaly and executing a physical fix.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] By formalizing accountability through structured workflows, these ecosystems improve engagement at the "action ownership" level, ensuring that data-driven insights lead to verified energy savings.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Another objective of Engagement is to connect occupants’ daily choices with building energy consumption.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] By displaying real-time consumption information, occupants see the immediate impact of their actions.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] The software can be used to promote energy conservation initiatives, offer advice to the occupants, or provide a forum for feedback on sustainability initiatives.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] People-driven energy conservation programs, such as those sponsored by Energy Education, can be highly effective in reducing energy use and cost.
[src:energy-management-software/energy-management-software] Letting occupants know their real-time consumption alone can be responsible for a 7% reduction in energy consumption.
[src:energy-management-software/energycap] In response to a growing demand for energy management software when PCs were in their infancy, Steven D.
[src:energy-management-software/energycap] Heinz founded OmniComp, Inc. in 1980 and launched the development of EnergyCAP predecessor FASER Energy Accounting.
[src:energy-management-software/energycap] FASER became widely used by retail chains, government, universities, school districts and property managers.
[src:energy-management-software/energycap] By the mid-1990s, FASER's thousands of users tracked an estimated five million bills a year valued at $2 billion.
[src:energy-management-software/energycap] FASER and OmniComp were purchased by Enron Corporation in 1996.
[src:energy-management-software/energycap] Following Enron's bankruptcy in late 2001, Heinz acquired the energy information assets and launched Good Steward Software, which was renamed to EnergyCAP, Inc. in January 2010.
[src:energy-management-software/energycap] The company was renamed EnergyCAP, LLC in March 2021 upon the establishment of a strategic partnership with private equity investment firm Resurgens Technology Partners.
[src:energy-management-software/energycap] The EnergyCAP platform integrates utility, commodity, meter, and sensor data into a single source of truth.
[src:energy-management-software/energycap] EnergyCAP’s core functionality is built around its **Utility Management** engine, which automates utility bill ingestion, audits billing errors, and offers advanced analytics for energy, sustainability, and finance teams.
[src:energy-management-software/energycap] EnergyCAP serves a wide range of industries including higher education, government, K–12, healthcare, commercial real estate, and manufacturing.
